'''Cooper Mountain Vineyards''' is an [[United States|American]] [[winery]] located in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]], [[Oregon]], United States. Started in 1978, the certified [[organic certification|organic]] wine maker produces [[Pinot noir]], [[Pinot gris]], [[Chardonnay]], and [[Pinot blanc]]. Located in the [[Portland metropolitan area]], the vineyard is sited on the western slopes of [[Cooper Mountain (Oregon)|Cooper Mountain]], an extinct volcano.<ref name="houston"/> 

==History==
The winery was founded in 1978 by Dr. Robert Gross and his wife Corrine and released its first vintage in 1987.<ref name="houston">{{cite news|title=An eruption of good taste in Oregon; Winery situated on ancient volcano is bursting with outstanding wines|last=Lonsford|first=Michael|date=March 15, 2006|work=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|pages=2|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref> The vineyards obtained state organic certification in 1995, and biodynamic certification in 1999.<ref name=WM>{{cite journal |last= Parks |first= Betsy |url= http://winemakermag.com/departments/778.html |title= Growing Organic Grapes: Tips from the Pros |publisher= ''[[WineMaker (magazine)|WineMaker]]'' |date= April 2008 |accessdate= 2008-07-31}}</ref><ref name=Cooper>{{cite web |url=  http://www.coopermountainwine.com/html/bkgrd_history.html |title= Our History |publisher= Cooper Mountain Vineyards |accessdate= 2008-07-31}}</ref> In 2004, the winery released a third tier of wine called Cooper Hill to add to its two existing tiers: Cooper Mountain Reserves and 5 Elements Series. The winery released its first [[balsamic vinegar]] in 2006.<ref name=Times>{{cite news |url= http://www.tigardtimes.com/sustainable/print_story.php?story_id=115221433443875000 |title= Welcome to vinegar country |publisher=''[[The Times (Tigard)|Tigard-Tualatin Times]]'' |date= July 6, 2006 |accessdate= 2008-07-31}}</ref> Current production at the winery is 18,000 cases.

==Organic==
All wines produced from Cooper Mountain are [[estate bottled]] and certified both [[organic certification|organic]] and [[Biodynamic agriculture|Biodynamic]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Mayfield |title=Spiritual Agriculture Produces Grapes That Are Easy on the Land |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-17857535.html |work=[[The Columbian]] |date=October 20, 1998 |accessdate=2008-07-31 }}</ref> Cooper Mountain was the first winery in the [[Pacific Northwest]] to produce all of its wines from 100% certified organic and biodynamic estate-grown grapes.<ref name=Kysela>{{cite web |url= http://www.kysela.com/usa/cooper.htm |title= Cooper Mountain Vineyards |publisher= Kysela Pere et Fils, Ltd. |accessdate= 2008-07-31}}</ref>  The organic certification was done by [[Oregon Tilth]], and the Biodynamic cerification was done by [[Demeter International]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Yamhill County pours on fine tastes|last=Nokes|first=Deston S.|date=December 6, 2007|work=[[The Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|pages=4|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref><ref name=Cooper/> The winery has 120&nbsp;acres of grapes in production, producing four [[varietal]]s ([[Pinot noir]], [[Pinot gris]], [[Chardonnay]], and [[Pinot blanc]]).<ref name="houston"/> 

This winery owns and manages four different [[vineyard]]s with organic and biodynamic certification. The names of the four vineyard sites are Old Vines, planted in 1978, Meadowlark, planted in 1982, Farmington, planted in 1998, and Johnson School, planted in 2000. Cooper Mountain Vineyards produces a no-[[sulfite]] Pinot noir called Life Wine. Cooper Mountain is the only winery in the state that is certified as biodynamic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Advocates of <U+201C>Ultra-organic<U+201D> farming say it creates better wines|last=Cole|first=Katherine|date=June 8, 2003|work=[[The Oregonian]]|pages=L07|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref>

